Phase XI: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of the south gallery cryptoporticus of the Propylaeum West. The temple north colonnade falls from south to north across the Propylaeum, damage is incurred on the Propylaeum Retaining Wall and the entire area is overburdened with soil and debris.

Opening elevations: Course 1: 893.57 m. Course 2: 893.72 m. Course 3: 893.89 m. Course 4: 894.05 m. Course 5: 894.24 m. Course 6: 894.43 m. Course 7: 894.59 m. Course 8: 894.75 m. Course 9: 894.92 m. Course 10: 895.09 m.

Locus 3 includes the later treads which make up the main Propylaeum steps. Composed of a combination of limestone and sandstone ashlars, these steps were built over the earlier steps of the Propylaeum in the south, and over a layer of fill and sub-treads in the north. The elevations of the courses of the steps are listed from north to south.
Covering of the earlier steps with fill, sub-treads and later steps constructed.
